2
00:02:52,256 --> 00:02:55,259
We got them agitated, didn't we?

3
00:02:59,847 --> 00:03:02,725
You ride with God today.

4
00:03:02,975 --> 00:03:05,019
You know I ain't got no religion.

5
00:03:05,853 --> 00:03:09,273
Do you not fear
the eternal hell that awaits you?

6
00:03:09,731 --> 00:03:12,150
I ain't planning to see it just yet.

7
00:03:18,282 --> 00:03:20,451
Good people of Helena.

8
00:03:20,534 --> 00:03:24,705
Good people of Helena! I am saddened

9
00:03:25,622 --> 00:03:30,418
because today Helena loses
one of her true sons.

10
00:03:30,669 --> 00:03:33,589
Now we've cleansed
the Mexican filth from our city,

11
00:03:33,672 --> 00:03:38,177
but the disease left behind
has infected our civility.

12
00:03:38,260 --> 00:03:39,428
That's right! You hear that?

13
00:03:39,511 --> 00:03:42,472
These brown heathens pushed
their carts through our land.

14
00:03:42,556 --> 00:03:46,060
And instead of uniting
against these indignations,

15
00:03:46,143 --> 00:03:48,437
we stand here divided.

16
00:03:48,520 --> 00:03:51,606
Watch yourself, Jesse.

17
00:03:51,690 --> 00:03:54,776
Abraham is trickier
than the devil in the shade.

18
00:03:54,860 --> 00:03:58,697
And so, on the challenge given

19
00:03:58,780 --> 00:04:02,117
to Abraham Brant from Jesse Kingston,

20
00:04:02,826 --> 00:04:07,247
in the way of a Helena duel,
are we now assembled?

21
00:04:07,331 --> 00:04:09,375
Take care of my boy if I fall.

22
00:04:11,710 --> 00:04:13,754
We will.

23
00:04:17,758 --> 00:04:20,886
Gentlemen, come forward.

24
00:04:21,595 --> 00:04:26,934
God made this world, Jesse, and it
pains me little to send you from it.

25
00:04:31,563 --> 00:04:37,235
You shall pour out each other's blood
and we will cover it with dust.

26
00:04:37,861 --> 00:04:43,075
Whomever bleeds
the dirt red the most today,

27
00:04:43,825 --> 00:04:46,745
his deeds shall not be forgotten.

28
00:06:13,290 --> 00:06:16,668
You distinguished yourself
honorably against the Cheyenne.

29
00:06:16,752 --> 00:06:19,838
It was the Comanche in my day.

30
00:06:19,922 --> 00:06:23,968
Either or, the most contemptible breed
of people, don't you agree?

31
00:06:24,051 --> 00:06:25,886
Perhaps.

32
00:06:26,345 --> 00:06:28,931
Or perhaps they're misunderstood,
Your Honor.

33
00:06:30,516 --> 00:06:32,727
I understand you have
a problem with a dead Mexican.

34
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:38,440
Not "a" dead Mexican,
Mr. Kingston. Dozens.

35
00:06:38,524 --> 00:06:43,779
The latest one is the nephew
of a Mexican general, Ernesto Calderon.

36
00:06:43,862 --> 00:06:47,366
He went missing
along with his sister some time ago.

37
00:06:47,449 --> 00:06:50,410
The general,
kicking up quite a fuss about it.

38
00:06:50,494 --> 00:06:52,955
He's threatening to bring
a battalion of Mexican soldiers

39
00:06:53,038 --> 00:06:56,751
across the border to look for his niece
and the man who killed his nephew.

40
00:06:57,042 --> 00:07:01,171
Now, I don't need to tell you,
wars have started over less.

41
00:07:01,255 --> 00:07:05,926
Now, all the bodies are turning up
in the same strainer in the river...

42
00:07:06,009 --> 00:07:08,094
about here.

43
00:07:08,178 --> 00:07:10,972
It's roughly 12 miles from Mount Hermon.

44
00:07:12,057 --> 00:07:15,769
I take it you've heard
the name Abraham Brant.

45
00:07:18,480 --> 00:07:21,525
Foolhardy stories,
tales from the war, mostly.

46
00:07:22,401 --> 00:07:24,953
They call him the Preacher, I believe.

47
00:07:25,028 --> 00:07:29,533
I saw him once in Kansas
just before the war.

48
00:07:30,534 --> 00:07:33,746
The ranchers near Wichita
were offering 50¢

49
00:07:33,829 --> 00:07:35,873
for every red scalp that was turned in,

50
00:07:35,956 --> 00:07:39,042
and Brant showed up with 1,000 of them.

51
00:07:39,126 --> 00:07:41,337
Red, Mexican, negro, it didn't matter,

52
00:07:41,420 --> 00:07:45,349
as long as they had
dark hair and dark skin.

53
00:07:45,424 --> 00:07:47,760
And later, I saw him
preaching to half the town

54
00:07:47,843 --> 00:07:52,389
with a spirit that I have
neither seen before nor since.

55
00:07:52,472 --> 00:07:54,808
And as God as my witness,

56
00:07:54,892 --> 00:07:58,396
I saw him lay his huge hand

57
00:07:58,478 --> 00:08:01,231
on this gimpy teenage girl.

58
00:08:01,315 --> 00:08:07,196
And he cured her with a touch,
like Christ himself.

59
00:08:10,616 --> 00:08:13,619
Pardon me, Your Honor, but...

60
00:08:13,702 --> 00:08:17,414
but you'll have me believe he simply
touched the girl and she walked?

61
00:08:18,040 --> 00:08:22,002
All the way to the church.
Married her the next day.

62
00:08:22,669 --> 00:08:24,921
I'm assuming he resides in Mount Hermon.

63
00:08:25,005 --> 00:08:27,466
He is Mount Hermon, Captain.

64
00:08:28,634 --> 00:08:33,597
Now you'll travel alone
under an assumed name and profession.

65
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:36,558
Time is of the essence.
Calderon's blood is up.

66
00:08:36,642 --> 00:08:38,435
Why not send me with a company?

67
00:08:38,519 --> 00:08:40,271
There's too much at stake.

68
00:08:40,354 --> 00:08:43,566
You simply find out if Brant
is at the root of these killings

69
00:08:43,649 --> 00:08:45,860
and wire me from Fort McIntosh.

70
00:08:45,943 --> 00:08:49,196
Once certain, I will commit in force.

71
00:08:53,492 --> 00:08:55,202
How long?

72
00:08:58,247 --> 00:09:01,208
I'm not sure.

73
00:09:01,291 --> 00:09:03,627
I think it's best
not to presume this time.

74
00:09:03,710 --> 00:09:05,962
You've only just now returned.

75
00:09:09,800 --> 00:09:11,552
What is it?

76
00:09:14,888 --> 00:09:16,598
David?

77
00:09:20,686 --> 00:09:24,273
The man I'm inquiring upon...

78
00:09:24,356 --> 00:09:26,859
Abraham Brant is his name.

79
00:09:26,942 --> 00:09:30,154
He may or may not be responsible
for some terrible things.

80
00:09:30,237 --> 00:09:32,114
It's my job to determine which.

81
00:09:34,408 --> 00:09:36,118
Go on.

82
00:09:36,410 --> 00:09:38,537
By some...

83
00:09:41,915 --> 00:09:44,709
strange twist of fate,

84
00:09:45,627 --> 00:09:49,548
Brant happens to be the same man
that killed my father 20 years ago.

85
00:09:52,801 --> 00:09:54,928
Now, I know what you're thinking,

86
00:09:55,012 --> 00:09:58,307
but truth is, men like Brant have
orphaned hundreds of boys like me.

87
00:09:58,390 --> 00:10:00,976
And it was my father's challenge.

88
00:10:01,059 --> 00:10:04,855
David, you know as well as I, you will
go there and you will kill this man.

89
00:10:04,938 --> 00:10:07,774
You don't know that. You can't know that.

90
00:10:07,858 --> 00:10:10,486
Why else would you be sharing this?

91
00:10:10,569 --> 00:10:12,404
I've never once heard you speak like this.

92
00:10:12,487 --> 00:10:15,782
I'm curious, that's all.

93
00:10:18,285 --> 00:10:20,662
They say he's been touched by God.

94
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:28,212
Marisol, I'll go where they send me.

95
00:10:28,295 --> 00:10:31,715
It's not as if I've been
chasing this man my entire life.

96
00:10:38,889 --> 00:10:41,183
I can ride as well as you.
You taught me to track...

97
00:10:41,266 --> 00:10:42,934
It's crazy talk.
We should change the subject.

98
00:10:43,018 --> 00:10:44,520
You're gone more than you're ever here.

99
00:10:44,603 --> 00:10:49,650
What happened to the Tompkins woman,
only a month ago, was south of Austin.

100
00:10:49,733 --> 00:10:51,869
And not just some rogue straggler
we've somehow missed,

101
00:10:51,944 --> 00:10:55,156
but a band of Cheyenne and Comanchero.

102
00:10:55,239 --> 00:10:59,618
Would you like me to describe to you
exactly what they did to that poor woman?

103
00:11:02,371 --> 00:11:06,633
This is coming from the governor himself.

104
00:11:06,708 --> 00:11:09,595
At least here, we both know you're safe.

105
00:11:09,670 --> 00:11:13,174
Since you took me, you come and you go.

106
00:11:14,550 --> 00:11:17,011
I'm left here with nothing to do.

107
00:11:17,594 --> 00:11:21,190
There's the Sheltons.
Donahues are less than a mile.

108
00:11:31,233 --> 00:11:35,237
Marisol, this is a job. It's my work.

109
00:11:37,239 --> 00:11:40,200
You can't expect me to put you
in that kind of danger.

110
00:11:41,827 --> 00:11:45,289
Then perhaps this time when you return,

111
00:11:45,372 --> 00:11:47,124
I will have left.

112
00:11:50,085 --> 00:11:51,670
Excuse me.

113
00:13:46,535 --> 00:13:48,120
You kill it, you clean it.

114
00:14:14,855 --> 00:14:17,274
You've never spoken about him.

115
00:14:19,359 --> 00:14:21,278
Do you miss him?

116
00:14:21,737 --> 00:14:25,241
From all accounts, Jesse Kingston
was recalcitrant and headstrong

117
00:14:25,324 --> 00:14:27,751
and got what he deserved.

118
00:14:27,826 --> 00:14:30,537
I figure he picked the wrong fight.

119
00:14:32,539 --> 00:14:36,376
What about you? You ever miss old Javier?

120
00:14:36,877 --> 00:14:39,129
You changed the subject.

121
00:14:46,887 --> 00:14:51,558
It's impossible to love someone
who hates their self that much.

122
00:14:54,019 --> 00:14:55,812
I miss nothing.

123
00:15:18,252 --> 00:15:20,004
Morning, gentlemen.

124
00:15:23,632 --> 00:15:27,052
Saw smoke. Thought we'd see
to some lodgings, rest our horses.

125
00:15:28,595 --> 00:15:30,889
What brings y'all this way?

126
00:15:31,265 --> 00:15:33,726
We're on our way to Ciudad Victoria.

127
00:15:33,809 --> 00:15:36,228
The map at Fort McIntosh showed a town.

128
00:15:36,311 --> 00:15:39,105
Mount Hermon, I believe.

129
00:15:41,900 --> 00:15:44,486
Someone had the good sense to chart it.

130
00:15:44,570 --> 00:15:47,198
We figured we'd practice the same
good sense to stop and make use.

131
00:15:47,281 --> 00:15:49,492
She family or help?

132
00:15:53,120 --> 00:15:55,706
My apologies. My name is David Locke.

133
00:15:55,789 --> 00:15:56,999
This is my wife Marisol.

134
00:16:00,878 --> 00:16:02,755
Of course, if there's
some trouble in town,

135
00:16:02,838 --> 00:16:05,716
we could return to Fort McIntosh
and pass on word for you.

136
00:16:10,721 --> 00:16:13,265
You need to see the preacher.

137
00:17:03,482 --> 00:17:04,984
Put that down.

138
00:17:38,100 --> 00:17:40,060
We have new guests.

139
00:17:40,143 --> 00:17:42,354
They're asking for lodgings.

140
00:17:42,437 --> 00:17:44,356
And they shall have it.

141
00:17:45,399 --> 00:17:48,068
Welcome to Mount Hermon.

142
00:17:52,531 --> 00:17:54,616
From where is it that you come?

143
00:17:54,700 --> 00:17:57,669
Houston, sir, by way of Fort McIntosh.

144
00:17:57,744 --> 00:18:00,080
My name is David Locke.
This is my wife Marisol.

145
00:18:06,962 --> 00:18:08,430
I'm Abraham Brant.

146
00:18:08,505 --> 00:18:11,133
You've met my son Isaac.

147
00:18:14,553 --> 00:18:16,805
He says welcome.

148
00:18:21,059 --> 00:18:24,563
I am Mount Hermon's mayor
and law when there's need,

149
00:18:24,646 --> 00:18:29,025
but I am unfailingly
the town's ethereal counselor.

150
00:18:29,109 --> 00:18:30,360
Marisol, are you religious?

151
00:18:30,819 --> 00:18:35,699
I'm spiritual,
but I do not like religion, sir.

152
00:18:35,782 --> 00:18:38,201
Me neither. And you, David?

153
00:18:38,285 --> 00:18:40,496
My wife and I are one and the same, sir.

154
00:18:40,579 --> 00:18:45,334
Please, we are not formal here.
"Abraham" works just fine.

155
00:18:47,503 --> 00:18:49,588
- Morning.
- Morning, Abraham.

156
00:18:50,631 --> 00:18:54,009
Here we are. Make yourself at home.

157
00:18:54,092 --> 00:18:55,677
Thank you, Abraham.

158
00:18:55,761 --> 00:18:57,471
All we need now is some rest.

159
00:18:58,180 --> 00:18:59,973
I'll leave you to it.

160
00:19:00,057 --> 00:19:01,976
Buenas noches, Marisol.

161
00:19:03,101 --> 00:19:04,644
Mr. Locke.

162
00:19:17,157 --> 00:19:19,326
We'll be here only as long as we need to.

163
00:19:19,409 --> 00:19:22,454
Just stick to the story, let me do my job

164
00:19:22,538 --> 00:19:26,500
and we can leave this place,
just as easy as we came in.

165
00:19:29,503 --> 00:19:31,472
Okay?

166
00:19:31,547 --> 00:19:33,174
Okay.

167
00:19:53,485 --> 00:19:55,070
Morning, gentlemen.

168
00:19:55,153 --> 00:19:56,905
What are you doing out here?

169
00:19:58,448 --> 00:20:00,492
I never let the sun catch me sleeping.

170
00:20:00,576 --> 00:20:03,162
And I enjoy acquainting myself
with any new place.

171
00:20:03,245 --> 00:20:04,997
How'd you find your cabin?

172
00:20:05,080 --> 00:20:06,873
It was fine, Abraham. Thank you.

173
00:20:06,957 --> 00:20:11,420
- And Marisol?
- She's tired, resting.

174
00:20:11,503 --> 00:20:15,557
If she's unsatisfied,
I could drop off another blanket,

175
00:20:15,632 --> 00:20:17,434
keep her warm.

176
00:20:17,509 --> 00:20:20,804
Well, it's a large bed.
I doubt you'd have a blanket big enough.

177
00:20:24,933 --> 00:20:27,686
Isaac, you go on without me today.

178
00:20:27,769 --> 00:20:29,980
Mr. Locke is going
to join me for breakfast.

179
00:20:30,063 --> 00:20:31,690
Well, I... I thought
we was going to go down...

180
00:20:31,773 --> 00:20:33,942
Do I need to hold your hand, boy?

181
00:20:41,825 --> 00:20:43,660
Forgive my friends, David.

182
00:20:43,744 --> 00:20:47,498
Their charming qualities
don't shine through at the outset.

183
00:20:49,041 --> 00:20:52,469
You strike me as an educated man.

184
00:20:52,544 --> 00:20:54,796
I've managed to fool you.

185
00:20:56,632 --> 00:20:59,009
You hide it from your eyes well,

186
00:20:59,092 --> 00:21:01,970
but it sits on your shoulders
plain as day.

187
00:21:02,054 --> 00:21:06,233
You are a man in search of something.

188
00:21:06,308 --> 00:21:08,143
Perhaps absolution.

189
00:21:08,936 --> 00:21:13,190
You don't strike me as the type
to hide his meaning in vocabulary.

190
00:21:15,651 --> 00:21:17,111
Indeed.

191
00:21:17,194 --> 00:21:21,115
We don't get a lot
of uninvited guests this way.

192
00:21:21,198 --> 00:21:24,868
So why are you here?

193
00:21:24,952 --> 00:21:28,080
There's no real plan to it.

194
00:21:28,163 --> 00:21:31,875
I inherited my father's
mercantile in San Antone.

195
00:21:31,959 --> 00:21:34,336
I ran it for some years.

196
00:21:34,419 --> 00:21:37,389
Things got rough. I was robbed, shot.

197
00:21:37,464 --> 00:21:41,134
Both of us felt it was time to move on,
head nowhere particular.

198
00:21:41,218 --> 00:21:43,470
My wife's family are in Ciudad Victoria.

199
00:21:43,554 --> 00:21:47,099
We figured we'd strike out in that
direction, stop in a place if we took to it.

200
00:21:48,267 --> 00:21:49,769
Not so strange, is it?

201
00:21:50,477 --> 00:21:53,522
Welcome to nowhere particular.

202
00:21:56,024 --> 00:21:59,027
Can't say it's the warmest welcome
I've ever received.

203
00:22:00,070 --> 00:22:03,115
We're protective of our little oasis.

204
00:22:03,490 --> 00:22:06,326
How long will you be staying?

205
00:22:06,410 --> 00:22:08,495
Long enough to rest, a few days.

206
00:22:10,873 --> 00:22:13,501
Perhaps I can convince you to stay awhile.

207
00:22:14,418 --> 00:22:16,587
Why? You've only just met me.

208
00:22:16,670 --> 00:22:18,922
I know people.

209
00:22:19,923 --> 00:22:23,927
And I can tell
that you're a man one can tie to.

210
00:22:25,095 --> 00:22:29,057
Perhaps I can help you find
what you're looking for.

211
00:22:32,394 --> 00:22:34,354
I'd have no trade in this town.

212
00:22:34,438 --> 00:22:38,984
Well, let's just say
a spot for town sheriff

213
00:22:39,067 --> 00:22:41,903
just opened up at this very moment.

214
00:22:44,948 --> 00:22:48,535
I get the feeling there's not
a strong demand for law here.

215
00:22:48,619 --> 00:22:52,206
- No.
- And I have no experience.

216
00:22:52,289 --> 00:22:54,291
Well, what do you need to know?

217
00:22:54,374 --> 00:22:57,294
Just let your moral compass be your guide.

218
00:22:57,377 --> 00:23:00,255
You're obviously strong, capable.

219
00:23:00,339 --> 00:23:01,924
You're actually being serious.

220
00:23:02,007 --> 00:23:06,637
Look, David, I like you and Marisol,

221
00:23:06,720 --> 00:23:09,306
and I'd like to see you stay awhile.

222
00:23:09,848 --> 00:23:11,850
Not so strange.

223
00:23:12,601 --> 00:23:16,146
No. No, it's not.

224
00:23:16,897 --> 00:23:18,482
Well, then, it's settled.

225
00:23:19,107 --> 00:23:21,776
Gentlemen, meet your new sheriff.

226
00:23:31,203 --> 00:23:34,123
Thought I might continue my ride,
take in some of your countryside.

227
00:23:34,915 --> 00:23:36,583
Splendid idea.

228
00:23:36,667 --> 00:23:40,379
As it happens, I have
my own fond recollections

229
00:23:40,462 --> 00:23:44,716
of the San Antone area from after the war.

230
00:23:44,800 --> 00:23:49,179
Small town... name of Helena.

231
00:23:49,263 --> 00:23:51,265
Might have passed through her
on your way here.

232
00:23:51,849 --> 00:23:53,017
Don't seem to recall it.

233
00:23:56,228 --> 00:23:58,731
Wild place is what I recollect.

234
00:23:59,439 --> 00:24:01,149
Hard to forget.

235
00:24:04,111 --> 00:24:08,324
Well, Sheriff, pick yourself a direction.

236
00:25:24,066 --> 00:25:26,318
Welcome to Mount Hermon, Marisol.

237
00:25:26,401 --> 00:25:28,069
We brought you both some food.

238
00:25:28,153 --> 00:25:30,739
And we just had to meet
the wife of the new sheriff.

239
00:25:30,822 --> 00:25:32,782
- Sheriff?
- Did you have a long journey here?

240
00:25:33,075 --> 00:25:34,076
Yeah, but...

241
00:25:34,159 --> 00:25:35,952
You are more beautiful than was spoken of.

242
00:25:36,537 --> 00:25:38,205
Who spoke?

243
00:27:02,247 --> 00:27:04,166
You live around here?

244
00:27:07,127 --> 00:27:09,296
I from Tamaulipas.

245
00:27:10,631 --> 00:27:13,592
Why have you come?

246
00:27:13,675 --> 00:27:16,270
To pray for the dead.

247
00:27:16,345 --> 00:27:18,097
You know about the bodies?

248
00:27:21,600 --> 00:27:25,229
Was it white men?

249
00:28:01,431 --> 00:28:04,017
They knew things, David.

250
00:28:04,101 --> 00:28:05,561
Who came?

251
00:28:05,644 --> 00:28:07,771
Women from the town.

252
00:28:07,855 --> 00:28:09,607
What did they want?

253
